### Description

I've been looking at case and found:
```
curl -uelastic:password -HContent-Type:application/json -XPOST localhost:9200/_query?pretty -d'{
    "query": "ROW a = [true, false] | EVAL c = CASE(MV_SLICE(a, 0, 2), \"foo\", \"bar\")"
}'


curl -uelastic:password -HContent-Type:application/json -XPOST localhost:9200/_query?pretty -d'{
    "query": "ROW a = [true, false] | EVAL c = CASE(a, \"foo\", \"bar\")"
}'


curl -uelastic:password -HContent-Type:application/json -XDELETE localhost:9200/test
curl -uelastic:password -HContent-Type:application/json -XPUT localhost:9200/test/_doc/1?refresh -d'{"a": [true, true]}'

curl -uelastic:password -HContent-Type:application/json -XPOST localhost:9200/_query?pretty -d'{
    "query": "FROM test | EVAL c = CASE(a, \"foo\", \"bar\")"
}'
```

These three produce incorrect output - the first two fail with class cast exceptions. The second produces `foo` instead of `bar` and a warning. This is because the implementation for CASE is from long before we had proper multivalue field handling.
